Final Project-Analysis of housing price in Beijing¶

Ziqi Yang

Introduction¶

The overall objective of this project will be to analyze the housing price of Beijing from 2011 to 2017.Throughout this tutorial, I will attempt to uncover potential trends between housing price and various indicators like house strcuture, district and the number of rooms. The original dataset is from : https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/ruiqurm/lianjia

Motivation¶

As a person who has lived in China for 16 years, I have often heard people complain that housing prices are so high that many people cannot afford to buy a house of their own in their entire lives. Beijing is one of the worst cities. As a city with a population of 21.89 million, many young people with dreams want to have a home in this city. From these data, we can see what the main household composition in Beijing looks like, and what factors will influence people to buy a house. Finally, we can also see the overall environment of housing market in China from the factors affecting housing prices in Beijing.

Required tools¶

I will use Python 3 with a few imported libraries: pandas, numpy, matplotlib, scikit-learn, seaborn, and more.

Exploratory data analysis¶

This is where we do the critical process of performing initial investigations on data so as to discover patterns, to spot anomalies, to test hypothesis and to check assumptions with the help of summary statistics and graphical representations. I am tring to use different types of plots to display the relationship between the price and all kinds of variables like district , year and building structure.

First, we need to create a graph of the relationship between year and price, so that we can observe the general trend of price.

Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Total sold vs Number of room')

From the graph above, we could see that number of the bathroom of all the houses sold in 2016 are between 1 to 3 and the number of the bedroom of all the houses sold in 2016 are between 1 to 5. Most of the house have only 1 bathroom and 2 bedroom. Regarding this phenomenon, I think it is mainly related to location and price. First of all, from the previous plot, we know that the location closer to the city center is more expensive. The city center is often where many people go to work, and many people choose a live so that it is more convenient to commute to company. At the same time, China implemented the one child policy for a long time until January 1, 2016. Although the dataset we used here is from 2016, most families still have only one child in 2016 which make sense that 2 bedroom house is more popular.

As far as I know, the best schools in Beijing are mainly concentrated in XiCheng district, DongCheng district and HaiDian district. This also explains why these three districts are the top three in this plot and the price difference is very small.

Correlation and Hypothesis Testing¶

Hypothesis Test:

Significance Level: α=0.05 Ho = There is no relationship between a variable and price/totalPrice Ha = There is a relationship between a variable and price/totalPrice

In [18]:
plt.gcf().set_size_inches((20, 20)) 
corr = df.corr(method='spearman')
sns.heatmap(corr, annot=True)     
plt.show()

The plot above shows all positive and negative correlation between each variables. If the number is negative which means there is a inverse relationship between two variables. Higher values of one variable tend to be associated with lower values of the other variable. When the number is greater than or equal to 0.7, we can say there is a strong correlation. However, we only have 2 number that is larger than 0.7 but we still have some number close to it. We can see that totalPrice and price has a strong positive correlation with each other since they represent the same thing. The price also has a strong positive correlation with communityAverage, meaning the dense population area always have more expensive house price. In addition, totalPrice and totalSquare also have strong positive correlation relationship which means the bigger house it is, the price is higher. The number of living rooms, bedrooms and bathrooms is very related to the size of the house.

Conclusion¶

Buying a house is never a small thing. Every small house can represent a person's goals, dreams and reality of society. Therefore, by analyzing the relationship between house prices in Beijing and various indicators, I have obtained some important findings. These indicators can be related to the price of a house somehow, and they can also affect whether a house it is easier to sell.

First of all, I think the price of a house is proportional to the surrounding schools zones. I believe this phenomenon is not only in Beijing, but everywhere in the world. The location of the house in the city is also a non-negligible indicator. The price of a house is often proportional to the average price of the surrounding environment. To my surprise, I found that the price of a house in the far suburbs was almost one-sixth the price of a house around Tiananmen Square. Correspondingly, people living in the suburbs have a lot less mortgage pressure than those living in the city center, but they will also pay more for transportation costs. Indicators are the basis of price, so I use these as my target characteristics. I use Exploratory data analysis and Correlation and Hypothesis Testing to show the relationship between these variables and price. However, there are still some issues not addressed in this analysis such as 1. Are low-priced homes easier to sell than high-priced homes? 2. If everyone can work from home in the future, reducing the time for commuting, will house prices continue to skyrocket in the city center? 3. Is it possible that house price trends will gradually level off?

I hope that seeing a data science pipeline from: Data clean , Exploratory , Data Analysis and Hypothesis Testing could give you some insight into how you can leverage data.
